    value: 뇌물을 써서 벼슬아치와 결탁하는 일을 이름.
english:
  title: The Biography of Master Floating-at-Leisure
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Floating-at-Leisure was the assumed name of the Recluse of Green Slope. The Recluse was forthright and unadorned, pure and austere, plain-spoken and honest. He neither bribed officials nor sought paths of power, neither attended feasts of welcome nor farewell gatherings, nor managed his household's commercial ventures. When fortune came, he did not consider abundant meals and fine robes as excess; when it did not come, he did not consider coarse clothing and poor food as lacking. By nature industrious, he loved studying the classics and histories. When someone mocked his seeming eccentricity, the Recluse replied: "Am I truly eccentric? I am eccentric in worldly affairs but not in learning; eccentric in how others see me, but not in how I govern myself. I read the classics to cultivate my heart, and histories to apply their lessons to my deeds. This is all there is to it. Am I truly eccentric?"

    The Recluse loved composing poetry. When someone mocked his clumsiness, he said: "Not so. Poetry expresses the emotions, encompasses universal principles, tests customs, and reveals good and evil. At leisure, inspiration strikes and thoughts emerge, dispelling the tedium of days. In public service, my verses become refined songs that illuminate the realm. Is this merely mockery and jest? In this world, those who chase profit while remaining ignorant of learning are the truly eccentric—not I."

    The Recluse delighted in playing the zither. When someone mocked his abandon, he replied: "I do not seek mere technical virtuosity, but harmony of the musical scales. I do not indulge in excess, but cultivate the virtue of equilibrium. I do not merely sing, but cleanse my heart of impurity and corruption. This is why the ancients never parted from their instruments without reason. Am I truly abandoned?"

    The Recluse loved exploring mountains and waters. When someone mocked his aimless wandering, he said: "Strolling through gardens brings appreciation of beauty. Occasionally fishing with peasants connects me to the fields. Thus a single day's leisure becomes profound joy. Do you think I rest my head on stone and rinse my mouth with streams, forsaking the world in solitude?"

    When asked about the way of self-cultivation, the Recluse said: "Be tranquil without striving, impartial without bias, poor without resentment, hardship without despair. Wander in thought-free ease, drift in praise-free freedom, hover in desire-less detachment, dwell in neither right nor wrong, fade into formlessness. Thus one approaches the Way and enters the realm of the perfected."

    When asked about his assumed name, the Recluse explained: "To live in the world is like floating; to depart from it is like resting. High carriages and swift steeds, silk robes and insignia worn along the roads—these are the accidents of office, not my possessions. To gather the spirit and still the breath, to transform the form until it returns to the earth—this is humanity's return to the true. From this too I cannot escape. If inwardly I find joy in the Way and life and death do not disturb my peace, then what glory is there in floating, what sorrow in resting? I follow the Way, not the allure of external things."

    At this, someone gasped and fled with widened eyes. Thus was this praise composed:

    The height of mountains—countless peaks piled to touch the heavens,
    The depth of waters—many streams gathered to form the abyss,
    The Way of the Master—all virtues joined to form the Great Whole.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Green Slope Recluse (靑坡居士): A scholarly pseudonym suggesting detachment and elevated virtue.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The zither (琴): In classical Chinese culture, the zither was considered an instrument of moral cultivation, not mere entertainment.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The realm of the perfected (至人之域): A Daoist philosophical concept referring to one who has transcended worldly concerns and achieved spiritual completion.'
